==English==

===Etymology===
Aeschylus's ''{{w|Agamemnon (play)|Agamemnon}}'', part of the ''Oresteia'', a trilogy of tragic dramas by the ancient Greek dramatist; it was first performed in 458 {{l|en|BCE}}. 
:* By the sword you did your work, and by the sword you die.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genius.com/Aeschylus-agamamnon-lines-1509-1558-annotated |title=Aeschylus – Agamamnon (Lines 1509-1558) |website=Genius.com |date=2014-08-01 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last=Fagles |first=Robert |date=1984 |title=The Oresteia |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NtSGKcgMIlIC |location= |publisher=Penguin Books |page= |isbn=9780140443332 |author-link= }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/oresteiaofaeschy00aescuoft?ref=ol#page/62/mode/2up/search/sword |title=The Agamamnon |website=archive.org |date=1920-01-01 |accessdate=2017-07-26}}</ref>

'''1611,''' {{w|King James Version of the Bible}}, {{w|Gospel of Matthew}}, [[s:Bible (King James)/Matthew#Chapter 26|26:52]]
:* Then said Jesus unto him, "Put up again thy sword into his place: for all they that take the sword shall perish with the sword."

